summary: Is there any sort of Devil's Advocate position by which we can rationalize Varys & Tyrion debating a Jon-Dany marriage for three...
question: Is there any sort of Devil's Advocate position by which we can rationalize Varys & Tyrion debating a Jon-Dany marriage for three weeks now without once bouncing the idea off one or both of them? Especially when they are already hooking up?  Like, I could see keeping mum if Sansa had to approve the marriage or there were reasons to think Jon or Dany would hate the idea, but that's not the case. In Doylist-land it would be way more dramatic if the kinship scuttled an engagement than a romance.
answer:
They explained the reason Varys and Tyrion didn’t support the marriage, and it was misogynistic as fuck: “She’s too strong for him.”

No, this is not a good reason, even in-universe. But then, Jon and Dany should have been discussing a political marriage round about 7.03. There have been no good reasons for this at any point; it was something that didn’t happen because if it did, the plot the writers wanted didn’t work.

body:
🤦🏾‍♀️

At this point, I’m not surprised that even people who obsessively read a book series does not always mean they understand it ( a la some Harry Potter fans).

It’s great to read a series for pure enjoyment. It’s great to really love characters and it’s fine to hate characters. BUT, when you allow that to overpower the narrative told, the ideas attached to that, and what the author is trying to say, you’re doing yourself and the narrative a huge disservice.

I’ve probably read less than 100 pages of ASOIAF, but I’ve seen every episode of GOT. Other than that, I know a few key parts in the books and that’s it. The sad part about this is that I have more of a better understanding than some of who read the books. Like, straight up. Most of the misconceptions I’ve had about the series comes from other people’s head canons.

But, when I rely on my own knowledge and ability to reference past events or passages than I know of, my grip of certain characters far exceed those who have read each book front to back and, some, several times.

When I consume media, it’s not just for enjoyment and pleasure, I read to understand what I’m being told. Because of this, I’m able to discern what’s good and bad writing. I’m able to differentiate between me disliking good storytelling from me having an issue between bad storytelling.

Case in point: Arya

People got a lot to shit to say about her, but Arya fans provided several passages that disprove many accusations lobbed at her. I can disprove most of this shit just from the show’s source material, but the actual passages…whew chile, this evidence is irrefutably and unambiguously obliterates everything the naysayers have said.

Such as:

Arya being a soulless killer

Being a loner

Not being maternal

Not knowing how to manage a castle (good with books and numbers)

Not wanting love


There’s a ton of other shit, but when you don’t read to comprehend, analyze, and provide good faith critique, you end up with egg on your face.

Dany is quite an interesting case as well because, as complex as she is, people distort everything she does to push Mad!Dany theories. HELL, Dany COULD go mad, but the evidence they use lacks context and defies logic as to how any rational person would react in an emotionally trying situation.

Like, I’m so down and tired of this community and their basic ass comprehension and analytical skills.
